post_text:
On August 10, 2020, the Wilkes County Schools Board of Education voted to open the 2020-2021 School Year under Plan C, with the goal of transitioning to Plan B effective Tuesday, September 8, 2020. As with everything related to COVID, this date for transitioning to Plan B could change if we were to see changes in local metrics or data.

Please keep in mind that due to local metrics, individual schools or our entire system may have to operate under Plans A, B or C at various times during the school year. Our goal will be to provide you as much notice as possible before changes in the delivery of instruction have to be made.
text:
On August 10, 2020, the Wilkes County Schools Board of Education voted to open the 2020-2021 School Year under Plan C, with the goal of transitioning to Plan B effective Tuesday, September 8, 2020. As with everything related to COVID, this date for transitioning to Plan B could change if we were to see changes in local metrics or data.

Please keep in mind that due to local metrics, individual schools or our entire system may have to operate under Plans A, B or C at various times during the school year. Our goal will be to provide you as much notice as possible before changes in the delivery of instruction have to be made.

post_text: Under Plan C, you can still expect a typical instructional day. Teachers will be doing instructional lessons through their remote instruction platform during the times listed below or their lessons may be recorded and viewable later in the day. (Some times may vary slightly per school.) Grades K-5 will be using Seesaw or Google Classroom. Grades 6-12 will be using Canvas. Students can choose to tune in for instruction or on their own schedule by watching recorded lessons.

post_text:
WCS families, based on advice we received today from our local health director and after consulting with our Board of Education, Wilkes County Schools will now open the 2020-2021 school year under Plan C. Under Plan C, all students will participate in remote learning only.
‚Ä¢
A timeline for transitioning from Plan C to Plan B will be determined early next week. You will receive information concerning how Plan C will look for your child from their school next week.
‚Ä¢
While we know this is a change and may present challenges, please understand that this decision was made in the best interest of the safety of both our students and our staff.

-
Remote Learning is available as an option for any family who does not wish for their child to attend under Plan B. Students who choose to attend WCS through remote learning will have the same expectations as those students who are under Plan B learning on a face-to-face A/B day schedule.
-
If you wish to enroll your child in remote learning only, please click on the link below to complete the enrollment form. The deadline to complete the form is July 31, 2020.

As we‚Äôre sure you are aware, Governor Cooper announced today that school buildings across our state will not reopen for students for the 2019-2020 school year. Wilkes County Schools will continue remote learning through the end of the school year on May 29. We feel this is best to prepare your child for success at their next grade level. We will continue to reach out to ensure your child‚Äôs health and well-being. Our goal is to continue to serve the students of this county even if school buildings are not open.

The latest information about grading for the Spring Semester is available on our district website (wilkescountyschools.org)

Meal Service will continue through the month of May.

Thank you for your understanding as we continue to provide your child with the best educational opportunity possible!

post_text: Congratulations to NWHS students Keaton H. and Liz M! They were selected by the NCSHSAA for the Heart of a Champion Award because of their outstanding sportsmanship!
shared_text:
North Wilkes High School
April 1 at 3:53 PM ¬∑

Congratulations to Liz M. & Keaton H. for being named "Heart of a Champion" by NCHSAA.

Each of the NCHSAA member schools can nominate one male and one female student-athlete. The students must have participated in at least one varsity sport or activity, including cheerleading, during the 2019-2020 school year, have not been ejected from any contest, and must have demonstrated outstanding citizenship and sportsmanship during their high school careers.

Way to go Liz & Keaton! Thank you both for always representing North Wilkes in a positive manner on and off the field/court.

Per the executive order of Governor Cooper, Wilkes County Schools will be closed for students through May 15, 2020.

Even though students are not in school, we are committed to staying as connected as possible. Teachers are introducing remote learning options to keep students engaged. Our buildings are open and providing essential services such as our breakfast and lunch service and support for our families. We appreciate our employees working hard to take care of our students. We are in this together!

post_text: Yesterday was a great day of learning for students at West Wilkes High School! They hosted their first World of Opportunities Conference! Representatives from our community came to speak with students about experiences and a variety of opportunities in our world! Areas such as dance, cosmetology, NC highway patrol, financial planning, realty, missionary work, women in leadership, movie making, photography, stress management, school leadership, and SO much more were available for students to explore!

post_text:
Effective March 12, 2020, Wilkes County Schools will suspend all field trips and will reevaluate this in early April.
Wilkes County Schools will follow the recommendation of the NCHSAA and suspend the Spring Sports Season at the conclusion of tonight's games (Thursday, March 12, 2020). This decision impacts practices as well as scheduled games for both middle and high schools and will be reevaluated in early April as well.
Per the Governor's recommendation, all gatherings of more than 100 people should be postponed. The Governor did not recommend school closings at this time.
We appreciate your understanding as we make decisions to ensure the safety of our students and staff.

post_text: Don't forget, Plugged-In Parents is tomorrow night! Parents, this is a great opportunity to learn ways to engage and communicate with your kids about their social media use!
shared_text:
Wilkes County Schools
October 15, 2019 at 12:14 PM ¬∑

Join us on Tuesday, October 22 at 6:30 PM at the Stone Family Center for Performing Arts to explore some of your biggest concerns regarding your child's media use. Together, we will address the biggest concerns parents have: managing screen time, getting a cell phone, cyberbullying, social media, and more!
